Now for the reverse direction: if `range f = Univ V`, then $f$ is onto.

If `range f = V`, then every element in $V$ is in the range of $f$. This means for every $v \in V$, there exists some $u \in U$ such that $f(u) = v$. This is precisely the definition of $f$ being onto.

